{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17499729","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17499729"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:01:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:01:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1521"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1521","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1521"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.13,0.03,0.45,0.26]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1521"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"33378"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1521","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1521"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1521"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"18792"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"456"},{"type":"tags","id":"934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8331"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8488"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12904"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37048"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"33378","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/33378"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 54-year-old farmer presents to his local General Practice with a two week history of ongoing left-sided abdominal pain. He has been previously well, reporting only the occasional episode of diarrhoea over the past few months. It was noted that he previously presented several years ago with diverticulitis that was treated symptomatically and spontaneously resolved. On examination he looks well, with a blood pressure of 132/84 mmHg, pulse 82/min and temperature 37.2\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. As part of the workup, the doctor arranges a plain abdominal X-ray (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely explanation for the radiological findings?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Swallowed foreign body","Tuberculoma","Renal stone","Hydatid cyst","Splenic abscess"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThere is a 3 cm homogenous lesion with a rim of calcification in the left upper quadrant. This has the characteristic appearance of an \u003Cstrong\u003Ehydatid cyst.\u003C/strong\u003E Whilst uncommon, these cysts are usually incidental findings on X-ray, with patients often being asymptomatic for many years as the mass gradually increases in size. The initial presenting symptoms may include left hypochondriac discomfort and a palpable mass due to the size of the cyst. On questioning, this man had spent most of his working life in an area where hydatid disease was endemic. In Australia these are the sheep farming regions. The usual primary host is a wild carnivore - or dog. The intermediate host is an ungulate - such as sheep. Man can be an inadvertent intermediate host, after ingestion of eggs that have been shed by the primary host (the farm dog). The eggs may adhere to the animal\u0027s fur and then be spread to humans by close contact. Since de-worming programs were introduced, hydatid disease acquired in Australia is now rare. However, this condition must be remembered in individuals arriving from parts of the world where the disease is endemic, particularly Africa, the Mediterranean countries and the Middle East.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe common sites for the development of hydatid cysts are the liver, lungs and spleen. In this instance, the lesion is almost certainly in the spleen. Given its location and appearance, it is almost certainly not a \u003Cstrong\u003Eswallowed foreign body\u003C/strong\u003E. This would be found in the lumen of the gastrointestinal tract.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Etuberculoma\u003C/strong\u003E is a well defined focal mass due to a disseminated mycobacterium tuberculosis (TB) infection. These are typically found in the lung post-primary TB infection, but can also develop in the brain and more rarely, in the spinal cord.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERenal stones\u003C/strong\u003E would be located lower, along the urinary tract and are smaller in size than the pictured structure, generally only a few millimeters in diameter. A non-contrast CT abdomen and abdominal ultrasound are the preferred diagnostic modalities for detecting renal stones.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Esplenic abscess\u003C/strong\u003E is an enclosed collection of pus within the spleen from haemotagenous spread of bacteria due to sepsis. On X-ray, these would not contain a calcified border and may also have associated gas within the abscess. Clinically the patient would likely have a major previous illness on history, with ongoing fevers and left upper quadrant pain.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["A hydatid cyst is often an incidental finding on X-ray, with patients often being asymptomatic for many years.","Hydatid cysts typically have a calcified internal wall, presenting as radiopaque on X-ray."],"references":["https://radiopaedia.org/articles/hydatid-disease","Keong B, Wilkie B, Sutherland T, et al. Hepatic cystic echinococcosis in Australia: an update on diagnosis and management. ANZ J Surg 2018; 88:26\u201331."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"18792"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1521"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19415"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19